[Currently, there are no vaccines for horses against Hendra virus. I
am unaware if any antivirals have shown any promise of working
against the virus or in the horse. - Mod.TG

According to the Institut de Veille Sanitaire (France) website as of
18 Jul 2008, 6 human cases of Hendra virus infection have been
confirmed (see
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/international/notes/hendra_180708.pdf>).

These human cases are listed in the following table in relation to
the known outbreaks of Hendra virus infection in horses in Queensland
and New South Wales.

Year (month) / place / equine cases / human cases / human deaths
-----------------------------------------------------------------
1994 (August) / MacKay / 2 / 2 (symptomatic ) / 1
1994 (September) Hendra (Brisbane) / 13* / 0 / 0
1995 (October) / MacKay / 2 / 1 / 1
1999 (January) / Cairns / 1 / 0 / 0
2004 (October) / Cairns / 1** / 1 (asymptomatic) / 0
2004 (December) / Townsville / 1 / 0 / 0
2006 (June) / Peachester / 1 / 0 / 0
2006 (October) / Peachester / 1 / 0 / 0
2007 (June) / Peachester / 1 / 0 / 0
2007 (July) / Clifton Beach / 1 / 0 / 0
2008 (July) / Redlands (Brisbane) / 4 / 2*** / 0
2008 (July) / Cannonvale / 1 / 0 / 0

Total / QLD + NSW / 29**** / 6 / 2

Footnotes:
*7 other horses euthanised
**probable case ;
***one asymptomatic human case
****includes one probable case

The figures above do not indicate any trend in the virulence of
Hendra virus for humans. - Mod.CP

See a photo of a fruit bat, _Pteropus_ spp., at:
<http://www.naturephoto-cz.eu/pic/sevcik/pteropus-giganteus--pteropus-giganteus-3.jpg>
- Mod.JW

